    "summary": "Erwin works as policy officer public transport at provincial government Utrecht. His prime focus is public transport network development with due regard to the appropriate balance between land use and transport. His background as urban and regional planner provides him the ability to understand and subsequently optimise interrelationships within multidisciplinary projects. \n\nHe feels strongly about the interface between land use and transport planning and is a big advocate of an incremental approach to planning and implementation of public transport. He has communicated his views and ideas at a number of transport conferences and published in professional magazines. \n\nA selection of projects is provided below (projects of previous employers included)\n\n- Feasibility Studies for Regional Rail service improvement between \u2018s-Hertogenbosch \u2013 Nijmegen and 's-Hertogenbosch \u2013 Geldermalsen - Tiel (The Netherlands, 2008 and 2009).\n- Western Cape Provincial Land Transport Framework 2011 \u2013 2016 (South Africa, 2011).\n- Cape Town Integrated Transport Plan 2006 -2011 and 2013 - 2018 (South Africa, 2011 and 2013).\n- Pre-feasibility study Lanedi station precinct in Soweto (South Africa, 2011).\n- Concept development and improvement of the Cape Town CBD Public Transport Hub (South Africa, 2012-2013).\n- Transport Studies Cape Town International Airport 2040 (South Africa, 2013).\n- Improvement of Regional Rail corridor - Maaslijn 2025 and beyond (The Netherlands, 2013).\n- Feasibility and Preliminary Design Al Dammam Regional Public Transport Network (Saudi Arabia, 2013-2014)\n- Feasibility Study Airport Express Train - Samara Rail Link (Russian Federation, 2014-2015)\n- Feasibility study Monorail Bandung (Indonesia, 2015)\n- Public transport operations plan City Region Utrecht 2016-1, 2016-2, 2017-1, 2017-2, 2018, 2019 and 2020 (The Netherlands, 2015-2019)\n- Regional Masterplan Utrecht BRT/U-link 2020-2023 (The Netherlands, 2018-2019)\n- Public transport strategy 2025-2050 (The Netherlands, 2021-2022)",
